notes:
pinned, single leg. ID confirmed by Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, Chimarra picea, and C. tapanti (and also Costa Rican specimens of C. limon) are very closely related. I speculated that they might have originated by introgressive hybridization between C. emima and C. jemima. The IDs are accurate. I would very much like to see sequences of Chimarra jemima, which is the other species that I thought may have been a parent species in the hybridization. The results are interesting, and I do not think that they represent errors in identification or sequencing.` Sep 12, 2008.|

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, C. picea, and C. tapanti are very similar (as is also C. limon). The lack of resolution is not surprising: this taxonomic problem was discussed in my dissertation. Chimarra emima and C. picea partially intergrade. C. tapanti appears to be a distinct species, but possibly very recently emerged.` Oct 26, 2009.

notes:
pinned, single leg. ID confirmed by Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, Chimarra picea, and C. tapanti (and also Costa Rican specimens of C. limon) are very closely related. I speculated that they might have originated by introgressive hybridization between C. emima and C. jemima. The IDs are accurate. I would very much like to see sequences of Chimarra jemima, which is the other species that I thought may have been a parent species in the hybridization. The results are interesting, and I do not think that they represent errors in identification or sequencing.` Sep 12, 2008.|

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, C. picea, and C. tapanti are very similar (as is also C. limon). The lack of resolution is not surprising: this taxonomic problem was discussed in my dissertation. Chimarra emima and C. picea partially intergrade. C. tapanti appears to be a distinct species, but possibly very recently emerged.` Oct 26, 2009.

notes:
pinned, single leg. ID confirmed by Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, Chimarra picea, and C. tapanti (and also Costa Rican specimens of C. limon) are very closely related. I speculated that they might have originated by introgressive hybridization between C. emima and C. jemima. The IDs are accurate. I would very much like to see sequences of Chimarra jemima, which is the other species that I thought may have been a parent species in the hybridization. The results are interesting, and I do not think that they represent errors in identification or sequencing.` Sep 12, 2008.|

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, C. picea, and C. tapanti are very similar (as is also C. limon). The lack of resolution is not surprising: this taxonomic problem was discussed in my dissertation. Chimarra emima and C. picea partially intergrade. C. tapanti appears to be a distinct species, but possibly very recently emerged.` Oct 26, 2009.

C. odonta complex (undetermined). pinned, single leg|

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra odonta probably represents a complex of forms. All of these would probably be included in one species under casual taxonomy. I wanted to get some estimate of how much genetic diversity was really involved as a preliminary to working on this group. Not all of the forms were represented in the material I sent you, because we only had 1 or 2 specimens of some of them, which would end up being holotype specimens if they represent new species.` - Aug 5, 2009.

Roger Blahnik: `Except for the above specimens, the specimens identified as C. villalobosi and V. wilcuma appear to be identified correctly, despite coming out together. This may be another case of incomplete lineage sorting. The species are allopatric, as far as is known, but are quite diagnosible. They are as distinct as most other species in this species group. ` - Oct 26, 2009.

notes:
pinned, single leg. ID confirmed by Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, Chimarra picea, and C. tapanti (and also Costa Rican specimens of C. limon) are very closely related. I speculated that they might have originated by introgressive hybridization between C. emima and C. jemima. The IDs are accurate. I would very much like to see sequences of Chimarra jemima, which is the other species that I thought may have been a parent species in the hybridization. The results are interesting, and I do not think that they represent errors in identification or sequencing.` Sep 12, 2008.|

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, C. picea, and C. tapanti are very similar (as is also C. limon). The lack of resolution is not surprising: this taxonomic problem was discussed in my dissertation. Chimarra emima and C. picea partially intergrade. C. tapanti appears to be a distinct species, but possibly very recently emerged.` Oct 26, 2009.

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra odonta probably represents a complex of forms. All of these would probably be included in one species under casual taxonomy. I wanted to get some estimate of how much genetic diversity was really involved as a preliminary to working on this group. Not all of the forms were represented in the material I sent you, because we only had 1 or 2 specimens of some of them, which would end up being holotype specimens if they represent new species.` - Aug 5, 2009.

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra odonta probably represents a complex of forms. All of these would probably be included in one species under casual taxonomy. I wanted to get some estimate of how much genetic diversity was really involved as a preliminary to working on this group. Not all of the forms were represented in the material I sent you, because we only had 1 or 2 specimens of some of them, which would end up being holotype specimens if they represent new species.` - Aug 5, 2009.

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra odonta probably represents a complex of forms. All of these would probably be included in one species under casual taxonomy. I wanted to get some estimate of how much genetic diversity was really involved as a preliminary to working on this group. Not all of the forms were represented in the material I sent you, because we only had 1 or 2 specimens of some of them, which would end up being holotype specimens if they represent new species.` - Aug 5, 2009.

notes:
pinned, single leg. ID confirmed by Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, Chimarra picea, and C. tapanti (and also Costa Rican specimens of C. limon) are very closely related. I speculated that they might have originated by introgressive hybridization between C. emima and C. jemima. The IDs are accurate. I would very much like to see sequences of Chimarra jemima, which is the other species that I thought may have been a parent species in the hybridization. The results are interesting, and I do not think that they represent errors in identification or sequencing.` Sep 12, 2008.|

Roger Blahnik: `Chimarra emima, C. picea, and C. tapanti are very similar (as is also C. limon). The lack of resolution is not surprising: this taxonomic problem was discussed in my dissertation. Chimarra emima and C. picea partially intergrade. C. tapanti appears to be a distinct species, but possibly very recently emerged.` Oct 26, 2009.
